objects.name: Returned Libra Mining Group
objects.description: Returned Libra, also known as 8220 Mining Group, is a cloud threat actor group that has been active since at least 2017. Tools commonly employed during their operations are PwnRig or DBUsed which are customized variants of the XMRig Monero mining software. The Returned Libra mining group is believed to have originated from a GitHub fork of the Rocke group's software. Returned Libra has elevated its mining operations with the use of cloud service platform credential scrapping.

objects.name: Campaign 2 - Docker Usage
objects.description: The Returned Libra Mining group has been witnessed to have performed cryptomining operations originated within Docker containers. These operations allow Returned Libra operators to access container management environments and while no container escape operations are currently known to exist, the poisoned containers do maintain root access and escape would be relatively trival.

objects.name: Campaign 1 - Tsunami Mining
objects.description: Targeting exposed Docker daemons, Returned Libra operators compromise the docker host and deploy new docker containers which perform cryptojacking operations. Initial compromised applications were found to include WebLogic (CVE-2017-10271), Confluence (CVE-2019-3396), and Apache Struts (CVE-2017-5638). Returned Libra also incorporated a Tsunami IRC botnet variant and has called their mining software PwnRig which is a customized version of the open-source XMRig mining software.
